  "prompt": "What is the difference between Dijon mustard and other mustards?",
  "response": "Dijon mustard differs from other mustards in several key ways:\n\n1. Origin\n- Dijon mustard originated in Dijon, France\n- Other mustards come from various regions and have different styles\n\n2. Ingredients\n- Traditional Dijon uses white wine or verjuice instead of vinegar\n- Many other mustards use vinegar as a base\n- Dijon typically uses brown or black mustard seeds\n\n3. Flavor profile\n- Dijon has a sharper, more tangy and intense flavor\n- It's typically smoother and creamier than other mustards\n- Less sweet compared to yellow or honey mustards\n\n4. Color\n- Dijon is usually lighter beige or pale yellow\n- Yellow mustard is bright yellow\n- Whole grain mustards have visible seed fragments\n\n5. Culinary uses\n- Dijon is often used in sophisticated cooking and French cuisine\n- Versatile in sauces, dressings, marinades\n- Other mustards might be more specific to certain dishes\n\n6. Texture\n- Dijon is generally smoother and more refined\n- Whole grain or spicy mustards have more texture and graininess\n\nEach type of mustard has unique characteristics, but Dijon is known for its refined, sophisticated flavor profile.",
